Chapter 1: Background Chapter
Introduction
The United States has seen notable increases in rainfall totals and flash flooding from 1959 to 2026, and outdated infrastructure has been struggling to keep up (Abegaz et al., 2026; Jaroszweski et al., 2010). This has affected not only human lives but also ecosystems nationwide. Specifically, in New England temperatures have risen, rainfall has increased, and extreme weather events have made flooding more common (Janowiak et al., 2018). Stream crossings are one type of infrastructure that has seen significant issues due to increased precipitation. Local organizations such as the Nashua River Watershed Association (NRWA) and regional organizations such as North Atlantic Aquatic Connectivity Collaborative (NAACC) are working to mitigate issues relating to stream crossings. In this project we will be working with the NRWA to explore culvert conditions and if failing culverts disproportionately affect specific communities. In this chapter, we cover climate change in New England and go over the impact this has had on communities there. We will then explore the methods to mitigate the impacts of climate change, and organizations involved in these efforts. Finally, we will introduce the north-central Massachusetts’ communities that will be the focus of this research project.
I.	Climate Change in New England 
Temperatures and sea levels are both on the rise globally and New England is no exception. Since 1901, mean annual temperature in New England has increased by 2.4 degrees Fahrenheit (Janowiak et al., 2018). At the same time, sea levels have risen by about 8 inches in that same time period (Sweet et al., 2022). Rising temperatures and sea levels can lead to more extreme rainfall and weather events and lead to flooding (Tippett, 2018). 
In New England, precipitation totals and the frequency of extreme weather events have been increasing since 1960 (Picard et al., 2023). While summer precipitation totals have been less affected, winter precipitation has gone up 12% just from 2002 to 2022 (Picard et al., 2023). Snowfall is on a downward trend and rainfall is on an upward trend (D. R. Easterling et al., 2017). Additionally, extreme weather events have increased. New England has seen the largest increase in 99th percentile wet day precipitation in the continental US (D. R. Easterling et al., 2017). The northeast has seen a 55% increase in extreme weather events between 1958 and 2016 (See Figure 1) (D. R. Easterling et al., 2017).

Figure 1: Percent Change in Rainfall in US (D. R. Easterling et al., 2017)
	Additionally, temperatures are expected to rise an additional 3-8 ℉ by 2100, on top of the already risen temperatures (Janowiak et al., 2018). Sea levels are also expected to rise 0.38m by 2050 and 0.5m by 2100 (D. Easterling et al., 2018). New England is expected to see an increase in annual heavy precipitation of four to five times the current rate by 2100 (D. Easterling et al., 2018). All of these trends have concerning implications for infrastructure, ecosystems, and future livability of populated areas.
II.	Impacts of Climate Change in New England
Climate change can cause damage to infrastructure, and aquatic life and also may disproportionately impact lower income communities. For the purposes of this research, infrastructure refers to roads, bridges, and culverts. A culvert is a tunnel-like structure, typically made of concrete, steel, rock, stone, or plastic, that allows water to flow under roads, railroads, or embankments. They are a road stream crossing that is used with the idea that the culvert will decrease flood and erosion risk (Mukherjee et al., 2024). They are designed to manage water flow, such as streams or stormwater, preventing erosion and flooding without requiring a full bridge. Common shapes include round pipes, arches, and boxes (See Figure 2). The increased flooding that comes with climate change damages roads, bridges, and culverts, which can disrupt transportation, isolate communities, and impede emergency services (Sydor-Estable et al., 2025). Along with this increase in flooding comes an increase in flow rate.
Fastmoving water can exacerbate erosion and lead to infrastructure failures. Emergency infrastructure failures are extremely costly, with reactive repairs typically costing 30% to 40% more than proactive maintenance and large-scale highway culvert replacements often costing between $500,000 and $1,200,000 (MassDOT, 2025). Beyond direct construction, these failures trigger indirect economic losses through road closures that can cost regional economies millions of dollars per day in lost commerce and emergency service delays. They can interrupt emergency services and commutes. If a culvert fails, it can flood the road making the road impassable for a time. Not only will this water make it hard for passing cars, but it can also wash debris onto the road or erode the shoulders of the road  (Abegaz et al., 2024). New England has a history that shows that culvert failures in storms and isolate vulnerable communities (Mukherjee et al., 2024). When culverts are in poor condition, these impacts can be exacerbated and negatively impact aquatic ecosystems (Sydor-Estable et al., 2025).  Stormwater runoff can increase nutrient concentration, which can make ecosystems chemically unbalanced and lead to decreases in biodiversity (Kamanmalek & Alamdari, 2024). This is why assessments are so important for preserving habitats. 
Also, flood events mobilize sediment, nutrients, and pollutants, negatively impacting water quality and aquatic ecosystems (Huckins, 2015). Excess sediment can smother fish spawning areas, reduce oxygen levels, and degrade habitat for invertebrates critical to the food web. In the example of sediment destroying fish spawn, this means that the fish population will decrease while species that are prey for fish, such as insects, will rapidly increase. The prey will then over eat leading to habitat destruction because of the imbalance in the food web. On the other hand, if the fish spawn are not destroyed and the insects habitats are destroyed this could lead to the fish starving, shrinking fish populations and compromising biodiversity (Jones & Hale, 2020). Part of this problem is that there is little management or assessment tools made available for this (Kamanmalek & Alamdari, 2024). Communities that lack political or financial power are often hurt more because they don’t have access to timely assessments.
Communities with limited political and financial  resources are disproportionately affected by infrastructure failures and flooding, highlighting the intersection of environmental risk and social equity (Jaroszweski et al., 2010; Zheng et al., 2025). This divide is exacerbated by the increased effects of climate change (Jaroszweski et al., 2010; Zheng et al., 2025). High-quality and strategically placed infrastructure is frequently absent in marginalized communities. Because these communities often lack the systems necessary to mitigate runoff, heavy rainfall can lead to pollutant levels—including heavy metals and bacteria—that are 10 to 100 times higher than in modernized zones, significantly increasing the risk of waterborne diseases (Kamanmalek & Alamdari, 2024). This infrastructure deficit directly correlates to a heightened public health burden, as seen in the $3.3 billion spent annually on treating waterborne illnesses that disproportionately affect low-income and minority populations (CDC, 2025; Kamanmalek & Alamdari, 2024). Communities that don't have political influence or enough funding have trouble maintaining at risk infrastructure. This leads to an increase in flood risk and all the risks that come with increased flooding such as public health risks and collapsed roads  (Abegaz et al., 2024). Ethnic and racial minorities also face higher flood risk (See Figure 3) (Flores et al., 2025). 

Figure 3: Flood risk by Demographic (Smiley, 2020)
Once an at risk community is hit with a flood, they also face prolonged recovery times as well as major disruptions to everyday live like difficulties in transportation, water pollution, and emergency services Vulnerable populations also face longer recovery times and greater disruptions to transportation, water, and emergency services after extreme events (Mukherjee et al., 2024). Socioeconomic backgrounds can affect if communities get funding for infrastructure and how often that infrastructure is assessed (Asadifakhr et al., 2025). Given the breadth of climate change impacts, communities need numerous mitigation tools in their toolbox. 

III.	Mitigating Impacts of Climate Change
As climate change impacts increase, it is important for communities to be resilient. A resilient community has the ability to "absorb disturbance and reorganize" after a disaster 
(Janowiak et al., 2018). Towns build resilience by upgrading roads and bridges so that the town can recover faster after a storm. Communities that use multiple methods to mitigate 
climate risks are often more successful in these efforts. For example, putting in "fish-friendly" open-bottom culverts while also protecting natural floodplains work better than only
using one type of engineering (Mukherjee et al., 2024). Combined methods can help keep the water clean and prevent topsoil from washing away when huge 100-year storms hit. Trees and 
plants along riverbanks are another useful mitigation method. The trees and plants soak up rain and keep dirt from getting into the water. According to Abegaz et al. (2024), land-use 
planning is important because, when done right, it prevents people from building in flood zones. Neighborhoods and natural nature sites are able to recover faster from flooding. The 
combination of natural and man-made strategies helps protect wildlife and keep the water clean as climate change makes storms worse.
Culverts and stream crossings connect ecosystems and are effective at keeping infrastructure in good condition for longer periods of time. When culverts are carefully designed to be as 
effective as possible, they can reduce flood risk, improve aquatic systems connectivity, and decrease erosion and sediment transportation (Huckins, 2015). Multiple studies have shown that
to improve fish migration between bodies of water, decrease habitat fragmentation, and keep roads from being washed out during floods having passable and correctly sized culverts are
essential (Jones & Hale, 2020; Sydor-Estable et al., 2025). Also, culverts that have ecological design principles are shown to extend the effective time period of culverts as well as
reducing costs of maintenance (Mukherjee et al., 2024). Properly designed and kept culverts can help avoid environmental damage and increase water connectivity while decreasing flood risk. 
New England has around 25,000 culverts  and small bridges (Massachusetts Division of Ecological Restoration (DER)). This sizable number means communities need a clear assessment framework 
to maintain their effectiveness. The NAACC  has developed standard assessment protocols which keep data collection consistent across a 13 state region from Maine’s to West Virginia’s 
watersheds. NAACC assessments evaluate hydraulic capacity, structural condition, and aquatic connectivity at stream crossings. The data can also be used to understand flood risk, ecosystem 
impacts, and infrastructure vulnerability in surrounding areas. The data collected from these assessments can be used to prioritize culvert repairs (NAACC, 2019). This ensures evidence based
prioritization of at risk culverts and makes data for ensuring proper resource allocation available. Early detection of culvert failure is extremely important in preventing massive failures 
of culverts and helps reduce costs of flooding both financially and socially (Abegaz et al., 2024). However, not all communities are able to conduct these assessments nor maintain culvert
integrity. In a study in New Hampshire, researchers found that socioeconomic backgrounds may impact funding and whether communities with failing culverts get the resources they need to
maintain or repair culverts (Asadifakhr et al., 2025). Most culverts are undersized, being too small in diameter, which can block fish and wildlife movement. This also increases flood hazards 
for communities because the volume of water being drained by the culvert is less than the volume of water entering. Regular culvert assessments save money and resources by preventing costly 
culvert failures. Because culvert assessments are important, it is also important to have assessment standards.

IV.	Culvert Assessment and Prioritization
State regulations issued by the Army Corps and revised by MassDEP, require culverts to meet the Stream Crossing Standards. These requirements include: the water carrying capacity of
the stream; the ability for the stream bank to be used for wildlife breeding, refuge, and food for fisheries; and the ability to have important habitat functions (Ecological 
Restoration Stream Crossings Projects, 2014). The Division of Ecological Restoration supports communities in replacing undersized culverts and offers financial assistance through the 
Culvert Replacement Municipal Assistance Grant Program (Mass.Gov, n.d.). To assist with upholding these standards, the NAACC provides a format and database for stream crossings assessments.
The NAACC is a network of individuals from universities, organizations, and more that focuses on improving aquatic connectivity across 13 states from Maine to West Virginia (NAACC, 2026).
The NAACC conducts research into stream crossings and all parts about them from water quality to organism movement. The NAACC’s research is used as a standard throughout the 13 states 
they operate. Certain researchers have found that the NAACC’s research into certain topics, like brook trout passage at road culverts in Pennsylvania, are lacking because they primarily 
focus on physical structural barriers while failing to account for biological and environmental variables, such as water temperature and flow velocity, which significantly impact the actual 
movement of brook trout through culverts and could be improved (Rogers et al., 2021). However, this doesn’t take away from all of the important means that the NAACC’s efforts are all for
naught. The NAACC is an ever developing and growing organization hoping to create means to protect the environment from adverse effects such as pollution and climate change. Yet they aren’t 
the only ones to do so.

The NRWA is a regional leader in natural resource protection and environmental education for all 32 of their watershed communities located in north central Massachusetts and southern New Hampshire (See Figure 4).

	   Figure 4: NRWA Towns (Nashua River Watershed Association, n.d.)
 The NRWA was founded in 1969 through the belief that everyone can make a difference (NRWA, 2023). The organization’s goal is to protect and advocate for water resources in the Nashua 
River Watershed. NRWA also protects land resources, stream crossings, addresses the impacts of climate change with nature-based solutions, uses hands-on science based education for
adults and youth, and builds an equitable and enduring organization (NRWA, 2023). NRWA recognizes that climate resilience efforts, like maintaining, repairing and replacing culverts may 
be inequitable. Consequently, they partnered with WPI’s Water Resource Outreach Center to explore this topic. In collaboration with the NRWA the goal of our project is to explore trends 
regarding whether socioeconomic factors impact the quality and condition of culverts in communities in the Nashua River Watershed. We introduce our methodological approach in the next chapter. 

Chapter 2: Methodology
Introduction to chapter 
The goal of this project is to help the NRWA look at stream crossing impacts and culvert assessments in Massachusetts, specifically in Lancaster, Leominster, Fitchburg, Rutland, and Sterling. 
We have outlined four objectives to help us complete this project goal. In these objectives we collect data, analyze it, and assess it for possible correlations. We discuss each objective 
in further depth along with their methods in the sub-sections below. 
