Objective 1: Develop Understanding of Culverts and the Assessment Process
	First to help us understand the culvert assessment process, we will complete participant and direct observation of culvert assessment, interview NRWA staff, and analyze the content of 
existing culvert assessment data. To begin, we will undergo training from NRWA staff following the NAACC assessment training guide (NAACC, 2019). This will include studying material and 
taking a test before we observe or conduct any assessments. Once we have passed the test we will shadow NRWA staff for 20 assessments to complete our training. While on these assessments 
we will have a chance to gain a better understanding of the real conditions of culverts and how they are assessed. We will interview NRWA staff about their experiences when assessing these 
culverts. They have far more experience than us as they have assessed over 1,000 culverts and are certified to train volunteers (see draft interview questions, Appendix B). They will be able
to help us understand some common conditions when looking at culvert disrepair. We specifically want to talk more with Utkir Adkhamov, the senior water equality associate at the NRWA, about 
these assessments and the state of culverts. 
	After this training and interviews with NRWA staff we will conduct content analysis of data and culvert roles in stream crossings. We will look at data in five Central Massachusetts towns: 
Lancaster, Leominster, Sterling, Fitchburg, and Rutland. This will allow us to have a better understanding of the quality of the culverts in these areas and in what areas they are failing. We 
will also analyze more articles and data on how culvert condition affects stream crossings and the roles of culverts in stream crossings. This will help us understand how different conditions 
can play a part in the effectiveness of stream crossings. 
____________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________
Objective 2: Determine Factors and Sources 
	Next we will gain a deeper understanding of the factors that affect culvert condition as well as the sources that can impact culvert disrepair. To do this, we will interview Utkir Adkhamov, 
the senior water quality associate at the NRWA, and NRWA staff once again . This time we will focus our questions on what common factors they notice when assessing culverts in poorer condition
based on their past experiences (see draft interview questions, Appendix B). We will also ask them about whether they notice any possible sources that can contribute to culvert disrepair. 
Because they have assessed over 1,000 culverts and have a lot more knowledge than the team on these assessments, Mr. Adkhamov and NRWA staff’s input will help us understand what factors affect 
the culvert conditions for assessment purposes. 
	We will then do a content analysis where we look into data provided by the towns’ Department of Public Works (DPW),  MassDEP, and the Massachusetts Office of Environmental Justice and Equity 
(OEJE). These sources of data may focus on culvert conditions as well as affecting factors and sources. Prior student projects identified public perception of the importance of culvert conditions
as a primary contributor to inadequate funding (Al Hakeem et al., 2023; Pagan et al., n.d.). Also, we will conduct content analysis on the socioeconomic background of communities by looking at
data from real estate rates in each town, insurance rates in each town with a focus on presence/absence of flood insurance, Office of Environmental Justice and Equity’s environmental justice
survey, and the American Community Survey. These sources can help us understand if demographics impact culvert conditions-culvert conditions. This would provide us with a better understanding 
of more prominent socioeconomic factors that are environmentally connected. 

Objective 3: Explore Best Practices in Culvert Prioritization 
	Next, we will explore the best universal methods for culvert prioritization, construction, and maintenance. We will analyze areas where experts have created long lasting, ecologically protective, and cost effective culverts. First we will do content analysis using the NAACC database to identify areas that meet all of the criteria listed. The NAACC database covers 13 states along the east coast. We will search for an area that stands out as exceptional (less than 2.5 percent of culverts with severe barriers). We will find the factors that lead to their success and find out if they are possible to implement in our focus areas in central Massachusetts. 
The next step will be to interview the Department of Public Works employees in  those communities to find out what they have done and how they did the assessment and repair (see draft interview questions, Appendix B). In line with the last objective, we will also use some of the data gathered from local DPW’s to influence our understanding. Once we have found factors influencing culvert condition positively we will explore which of these are realistic to copy. Some factors such as available funding and climate conditions may be beyond our focus areas’ ability to control.

Objective 4: Draw Conclusions and Come Up With Recommendations
	Finally, we will use the data we collected to develop recommendations for the NRWA. We will first achieve this goal by analyzing and compiling data we have collected throughout the other objectives. This will be done so we can find trends in the data to help support the creation of our recommendations and allow us to gain further insight into how culverts should be repaired.
	We will also be using artificial intelligence (AI), like ChatGPT or Google Gemini, and other data analysis tools to help draw conclusions and come up with recommendations to address any socioeconomic disparities that emerge from the data based on our data about the culverts. We will use AI to analyze the data we have acquired throughout all our objectives from the five communities of Lancaster, Leominster, Fitchburg, Rutland, and Sterling to see if any similarities or trends emerge. AI is the perfect tool for such a goal since artificial intelligence is known for its ability to detect trends and similarities along with giving quick comprehensive answers to any questions asked of it (Qureshi & Jeon, 2024). To confirm the accuracy of the AI assessment, we will spot check the results by cross referencing with older culvert data and other culvert in similar conditions to verify the new assessment and new data collected are concluded correctly. By following these four objectives, our team will be able to give the NRWA a clear plan for which culverts need the most help. This project will make sure that the repairs we suggest are good for the environment and helpful for the people living in these five towns.

